<http://www.nst.com.my/z//Current_News/MM/Saturday/National/20020713113032>

Malaysia: Upsurge of Cases in Selangor
--------------------------------------
Coffee shop talk has it that people are falling ill from dengue. Yes, and
the authorities' verdict is: it's alarming! But don't just talk about it
and do nothing. Go home now and check all the receptacles in your premises
to ensure they are free from mosquito larvae. Check your surroundings, too.
Making sure there are no breeding grounds for the dreaded _Aedes_ mosquito
is the best way to deal with the epidemic. Householders are warned that
more checks are being carried out at homes, and those found with mosquito
larvae in their premises will be fined MYR 500 [USD 131]. If the offence is
serious enough, the fine can go as high as MYR 50 000 [USD 13 165] or a
maximum of five year's jail, or both.
Yesterday, Selangor health chairman Datuk Tang See Hang gave some shocking
statistics; up till 6 Jul 2002, there have been 3156 dengue fever cases in
Selangor. So far 5 people have died from the disease, which is spread by
the _Aedes_ mosquito, which loves to breed in clean water. Of the 5, one
was from Taman Sri Serdang (Subang Jaya municipality), another from Section
27 of Shah Alam and 3 from the Selayang municipality - Kampung Sungai Bakap
and Bandar Country Homes in Rawang and Bukit Lagong in Sungai Buloh.
"There has been a 38 percent increase in the total number of cases so far
this year compared to the same period last year," he said. Most of the
cases were dengue fever while 183 cases were the more deadly form, dengue
haemorrhagic fever. From 30 Jun to 6 Jul 2002, there were 198 reports
statewide compared to 224 reports the week before, which was the highest
weekly figure so far this year. Of the total number of reports until now,
1222 cases or 38.7 percent of them were confirmed cases.
Tang revealed that of the 7 municipalities in the State, Selayang has the
highest number of cases at 711. The others are: Subang Jaya (506 cases),
Shah Alam (488), Petaling Jaya (334), Klang (226), Kajang (199) and Ampang
Jaya (193). [Control] measures being taken include fogging at all areas
where cases were reported, eliminating breeding spots, [destroying] _Aedes_
larvae and deploying residents to get involved in clean-ups. He said the
Government provides free fogging service and warned them that some pest
controllers were offering this service for a fee. "We provide free fogging,
usually in the mornings and late afternoons. These pay-per-fog operators
usually do it at noon. Don't deal with them." So far 10 stop-work orders
have been issued against construction sites; 8 by the Shah Alam City
Council and 2 by the Petaling District Health Office.
[Byline: Azlan Ramli]
