Honduras: More Dengue Hemorrhagic Fever Deaths predicted
--------------------------------------------------------
TEGUCIGALPA: Yesterday the government of Honduras announced that the number
of deaths due to dengue [hemorrhagic] fever in the past 6 months may
increase to 23. The official reports indicate that [as of Mon 15 Jul 2002]
the disease has been responsible for 9 deaths. The Minister of Health,
Elias Lizardo, pointed out that they are presently investigating another 14
deaths to determine if they were also due to dengue hemorrhagic fever.
This epidemic began on 6 Feb 2002 with the death of a 5-year-old child from
La Ermita, which is located 60 km to the north of Tegucigalpa. According to
official data, [as of Mon 15 Jul 2002] there have been more than 6262 cases
of classical dengue fever and 545 cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever
identified in the country. The principal population affected by the disease
are children and youngsters, ages 5-14 years, residing in 18 provinces in
Honduras.
The data that the health authorities have presented show that the majority
of the deaths have occurred in Tegucigalpa and surrounding areas, where the
health authorities have placed an epidemiologic cordon in order to prevent
further spread of the disease. "The situation is difficult... and the
population should collaborate to eradicate the disease, eliminate mosquito
breeding sites from their houses and yards. If th latter isn't done, the
eggs of the insect will persist and nothing that the government does
through fumigation of houses will eliminate the vector." the minister
pointed out.
With the arrival of the rainy season in the end of May, the Government
mobilized a large number of brigades with instructions to eliminate
standing water where the _Aedes agypti_ mosquito (the vector that transmits
the disease) breeds.
